</taxonomicName>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[164,779,1758,1903]" lastBlockId="21.[826,1441,198,557]" pageId="21" pageNumber="718">
<emphasis box="[164,527,1758,1780]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="718">
Larva and puparium (
<figureCitation box="[434,514,1758,1780]" captionStart="Figures 25–27" captionStartId="42.[144,234,1609,1630]" captionTargetBox="[146,1852,426,1576]" captionTargetId="figure-0@42.[144,1856,421,1580]" captionTargetPageId="42" captionText="Figures 25–27. Third stage larval Copestylum, whole larva, head to the right; scale bar = 7 mm. 25. Copestylum apiciferum; 26, Copestylum isabellina; 27, Copestylum sica." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5443496" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5443496/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="718">Fig. 26</figureCitation>
):
</emphasis>
Anterior fold with a wide band of spicules. Metathorax with two groups of a few indistinct spicules on the anteroventral margin (
<figureCitation box="[172,253,1850,1872]" captionStart="Figures 28–34" captionStartId="43.[164,254,1523,1542]" captionTargetBox="[496,1111,193,1490]" captionTargetId="figure-0@43.[494,1113,193,1493]" captionTargetPageId="43" captionText="Figures 28–34. Third stage larval Copestylum, body vestiture, black areas represent extent of sclerotization; scale bar = 1 mm. 28, 31, and 34, Copestylum quadratum, 28, long fine setae from the dorsum of the metathorax; 31, crochets from proleg on first abdominal segment, larger crochet = primary; smaller crochet = secondary; 34, branched setae from base of lateral lips; 29–30, Copestylum isabellina, 29, short, broad setae from the dorsum of the metathorax, 30, spicules from the anterior fold of the prothorax; 32, Copestylum hambletoni, broad based setae from dorsum of mesothorax; 33, Copestylum multipunctatum sp. nov., triangular shaped setae from dorsum of the anal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5443498" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5443498/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="718">Fig. 30</figureCitation>
). Dorsal vestiture comprising evenly sized setae except for anterodorsal groups of large, broad setae on the mesothorax and metathorax (
<figureCitation box="[1305,1384,198,220]" captionStart="Figures 28–34" captionStartId="43.[164,254,1523,1542]" captionTargetBox="[496,1111,193,1490]" captionTargetId="figure-0@43.[494,1113,193,1493]" captionTargetPageId="43" captionText="Figures 28–34. Third stage larval Copestylum, body vestiture, black areas represent extent of sclerotization; scale bar = 1 mm. 28, 31, and 34, Copestylum quadratum, 28, long fine setae from the dorsum of the metathorax; 31, crochets from proleg on first abdominal segment, larger crochet = primary; smaller crochet = secondary; 34, branched setae from base of lateral lips; 29–30, Copestylum isabellina, 29, short, broad setae from the dorsum of the metathorax, 30, spicules from the anterior fold of the prothorax; 32, Copestylum hambletoni, broad based setae from dorsum of mesothorax; 33, Copestylum multipunctatum sp. nov., triangular shaped setae from dorsum of the anal segment." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5443498" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5443498/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="718">Fig. 29</figureCitation>
) and smaller setae on middle transverse bands on abdominal segments 1–2. Abdominal segments 4–6 with second row of crochets inconspicuous and not as developed as on abdominal segments 1–3. Posterior breathing tube red-brown at base, dark brown at apex, below TR tube nodulate, above coriaceous. AP about a third as high to spiky rim as wide at TR (
<figureCitation box="[834,915,443,465]" captionStart="Figures 68–73" captionStartId="51.[164,254,1558,1577]" captionTargetBox="[323,1283,195,1525]" captionTargetId="figure-0@51.[323,1283,195,1528]" captionTargetPageId="51" captionText="Figures 68–73. Puparia of Copestylum, scanning electron photomicrographs, scales as indicated on images. 68, 70, Copestylum macrocephalum; 68, posterior breathing tube (prp), dorsal view width of TR = 1.3 mm; 70, prp, apical; 71, Copestylum posticum; pupal spiracles, dorsal view length = 0.93 mm; 69, 72–73, Copestylum isabellina; 69, prp, dorsal view width at TR = 1.1 mm, 72, pupal spiracles, ventrolateral view length 0.82 mm; 73, spiracular openings, apical and lateral views." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5443518" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5443518/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="718">Fig. 69</figureCitation>
). Pupal spiracles, about as far apart as a pupal spiracle is long and slightly curved in upper third. Openings coating upper half of one side, those at the apex with a short spiky projection (
<figureCitation box="[1301,1429,534,557]" captionStart="Figures 68–73" captionStartId="51.[164,254,1558,1577]" captionTargetBox="[323,1283,195,1525]" captionTargetId="figure-0@51.[323,1283,195,1528]" captionTargetPageId="51" captionText="Figures 68–73. Puparia of Copestylum, scanning electron photomicrographs, scales as indicated on images. 68, 70, Copestylum macrocephalum; 68, posterior breathing tube (prp), dorsal view width of TR = 1.3 mm; 70, prp, apical; 71, Copestylum posticum; pupal spiracles, dorsal view length = 0.93 mm; 69, 72–73, Copestylum isabellina; 69, prp, dorsal view width at TR = 1.1 mm, 72, pupal spiracles, ventrolateral view length 0.82 mm; 73, spiracular openings, apical and lateral views." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5443518" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5443518/files/figure.png" pageId="21" pageNumber="718">Figs 72, 73</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="718" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="21.[826,1441,613,758]" pageId="21" pageNumber="718">
<emphasis box="[826,1022,614,635]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="718">Taxonomic notes:</emphasis>
Very similar in larval characters to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Say" baseAuthorityYear="1829" box="[826,965,644,665]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="718" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="posticum">
<emphasis box="[826,965,644,665]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="718">C. posticum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from which 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Williston" baseAuthorityYear="1887" box="[1124,1273,644,665]" class="Insecta" family="Syrphidae" genus="Copestylum" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="718" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="isabellina">
<emphasis box="[1124,1273,644,665]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="718">C. isabellina</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs in the pupal spiracles being about as far apart as a spiracle is long and the openings at the apex having a short spiky projection.
</paragraph>
